{"Body": "<p>The College&rsquo;s high standard in the arts and humanities, underlined by its scores in the recent QS rankings, led to the construction of the new Long Room Hub. According to a spokesperson for the project, its aim is to &ldquo;feed into Ireland&rsquo;s smart economy&rdquo; through research and development.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">This is reflected in what Poul Holm, the academic director of the Long Room Hub research institute, said in support of the arts and the humanities, &ldquo;The arts and humanities are key to success in the global marketplace. Conventional wisdom is that technology and scientific discoveries are the main drivers of modern societies. Those working in the arts and humanities see things differently. The thought, the intention is primary to human action. The arts and humanities deal with the most driving force of all: motivation.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">The Hub, which cost &euro;6 million to build, is vital, says Dr. Holm, because &ldquo;very few people speak up for the arts and humanities.&rdquo; He believes that especially true at the high-powered tables where far-reaching decisions are made, and where too often the arts and humanities are treated as the &ldquo;ethical appendix&rdquo;. The Long Room Hub is intended to challenge this opinion towards the arts and humanities. The intent was to create a &lsquo;&lsquo;nerve centre&rsquo;&rsquo; for multi-disciplinary creative endeavour and advanced research, challenging existing approaches to the arts and humanities and introducing technology and creativity.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">Holm also highlighted the modern and non-traditional areas that the arts and the humanities have spread into, such as medical and environmental humanities. These expanded areas, he feels, are ones that arts and humanities departments should be increasingly consulted in.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">Provost Dr John Hegarty said the creation of the centre reflected the university&rsquo;s fundamental belief &lsquo;&lsquo;in the power of the arts and humanities to advance and enrich society at every level&rsquo;&rsquo;. There has been a further &euro;4.5 million, not counting private donations, invested in the Long Room Hub to initiate the research. The Provost continued by emphasising arts and humanities&rsquo; importance to future economic development. &lsquo;&lsquo;It also endorses the emphasis placed by the Trinity Long Room Hub on the imagination and cultivation of both creative and far-seeing graduates that will help define and drive a sustainable future.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">In the Hub&rsquo;s first year there will be 150 academics and 300 postgraduate students employed. Among these will be 35 academics from international universities who will conduct research, collaborate and address the application of the arts and humanities in the world.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">One of the more noteworthy aspects of the research institute is the transformative role it plays in involving the library in active research. Tim Keefe, head of digital resources and imaging services, digitised versions of an expanding catalogue of the institution&rsquo;s priceless artefacts. These are available online, which is driving up numbers of visiting researchers keen to study documents rarely found elsewhere. The Hub will employ six staff and six digestion staff working on various library projects.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">The Long Room Hub, labelled &ldquo;iconic&rdquo; by Dr. Hegarty, has been short listed for the world building of the year 2010, and will be open to the public on the 24th of September in line with culture night.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>The College&rsquo;s high standard in the arts and humanities, underlined by its scores in the recent QS rankings, led to the construction of the new Long Room Hub. According to a spokesperson for the project, its aim is to &ldquo;feed into Ireland&rsquo;s smart economy&rdquo; through research and development.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">This is reflected in what Poul Holm, the academic director of the Long Room Hub research institute, said in support of the arts and the humanities, &ldquo;The arts and humanities are key to success in the global marketplace. Conventional wisdom is that technology and scientific discoveries are the main drivers of modern societies. Those working in the arts and humanities see things differently. The thought, the intention is primary to human action. The arts and humanities deal with the most driving force of all: motivation.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">The Hub, which cost &euro;6 million to build, is vital, says Dr. Holm, because &ldquo;very few people speak up for the arts and humanities.&rdquo; He believes that especially true at the high-powered tables where far-reaching decisions are made, and where too often the arts and humanities are treated as the &ldquo;ethical appendix&rdquo;. The Long Room Hub is intended to challenge this opinion towards the arts and humanities. The intent was to create a &lsquo;&lsquo;nerve centre&rsquo;&rsquo; for multi-disciplinary creative endeavour and advanced research, challenging existing approaches to the arts and humanities and introducing technology and creativity.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">Holm also highlighted the modern and non-traditional areas that the arts and the humanities have spread into, such as medical and environmental humanities. These expanded areas, he feels, are ones that arts and humanities departments should be increasingly consulted in.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">Provost Dr John Hegarty said the creation of the centre reflected the university&rsquo;s fundamental belief &lsquo;&lsquo;in the power of the arts and humanities to advance and enrich society at every level&rsquo;&rsquo;. There has been a further &euro;4.5 million, not counting private donations, invested in the Long Room Hub to initiate the research. The Provost continued by emphasising arts and humanities&rsquo; importance to future economic development. &lsquo;&lsquo;It also endorses the emphasis placed by the Trinity Long Room Hub on the imagination and cultivation of both creative and far-seeing graduates that will help define and drive a sustainable future.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">In the Hub&rsquo;s first year there will be 150 academics and 300 postgraduate students employed. Among these will be 35 academics from international universities who will conduct research, collaborate and address the application of the arts and humanities in the world.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">One of the more noteworthy aspects of the research institute is the transformative role it plays in involving the library in active research. Tim Keefe, head of digital resources and imaging services, digitised versions of an expanding catalogue of the institution&rsquo;s priceless artefacts. These are available online, which is driving up numbers of visiting researchers keen to study documents rarely found elsewhere. The Hub will employ six staff and six digestion staff working on various library projects.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s1\">The Long Room Hub, labelled &ldquo;iconic&rdquo; by Dr. Hegarty, has been short listed for the world building of the year 2010, and will be open to the public on the 24th of September in line with culture night.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "771", "Heading": "Long Room Hub opens"}